Isolate label variable and scale data

#prep data, remove name variable, isolate status(y) variable
parkinsons=parkinsons[,-1]
status=parkinsons[,c("status")]
parkinsons=parkinsons[-c(17)]
#scale data mean 0, variance 1
parkinsons=scale(parkinsons)

Create the silhouette function to calculate optimal clusters

#create silhouette function
library(cluster)
# define a function to get the silhouette across different k
silhouette_k_sweep = function(cluster_fn, df, max_k=15){
  sil_scores = c()
  loss_scores = c()
  for(k in 2:max_k){
    # build cluster model
    g_k = cluster_fn(df, k)
    # get the loss for given value of k (requires different code for different cluster_fn)
    if(identical(cluster_fn, kmeans)){
      loss_scores[k-1] = g_k$tot.withinss
    } else if(identical(cluster_fn, pam)){
      loss_scores[k-1] = g_k$objective[1]
    }
    # get the silhoutte scores for all samples and average
    sil_scores[k-1] = mean(silhouette(g_k$cluster, dist(df))[,3])
  }
  # find the optimal k by find the max of the silhoutte scores
  opt_k_sil = which.max(sil_scores) + 1
  return(list(loss_scores=loss_scores, sil_scores=sil_scores, opt_k_sil=opt_k_sil))
}

Then, apply and plot the silhouette function for loss and silhouette score.

# apply silhoutte function to kmeans function and parkinsons data
sil_sweep_kmeans = silhouette_k_sweep(kmeans, parkinsons)
# plot loss across k (look for bend where loss begin to flatten out)
plot(2:(length(sil_sweep_kmeans$sil_scores)+1), sil_sweep_kmeans$loss_scores, 
     main="K-means Loss scores across K", xlab="K", ylab="loss score", type='l')

# plot silhouette score across k (larger is better)
plot(2:(length(sil_sweep_kmeans$sil_scores)+1), sil_sweep_kmeans$sil_scores, 
     main="K-means Silhouette scores across K", xlab="K", ylab="sil. score", type='l')

2 for silhouette and 3 for loss looks pretty good here.
